ordshire, England":"Hunsdon, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Saint Dunstan and All Saints Church, Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Saint Dunstan and All Saints Church, Stepney, Middlesex, England","Rye, Sussex, , England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England"},"en":{"about 1398–31 August 1472":"about 1398–31 August 1472","1394–1430":"1394–1430","1398–1472":"1398–1472","–Male":"Deceased","1413–1517":"1413–1517","1428–1486":"1428–1486","1430–1517":"1430–1517","–Female":"Deceased","1376–1399":"1376–1399","1472":"1472","1394":"1394","about 1428":"about 1428","1413":"1413","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1486":"1486","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","about 1398":"about 1398","31 August 1472":"31 August 1472","1517":"1517","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Hunsdon, Hertfordshire, England":"Hunsdon, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Saint Dunstan and All Saints Church, Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Saint Dunstan and All Saints Church, Stepney, Middlesex, England","Rye, Sussex, , England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shelley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places called Shelley (Essex, Suffolk, Yorkshire) or from Shelley Plain in Crawley (Sussex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>scelf</i> ‘rock, ledge, shelf’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish (Laois): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Sealbhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sealbhach</i>’, a byname from the adjective <i>sealbhach</i> ‘having possessions, wealthy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Shallow","meanings":["Irish (Kilkenny and Wexford): variant of   Shelley  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>shalou(e)</i> ‘shallow’, conjectured also to mean ‘thin’; perhaps also the same word in the topographic sense of ‘shallow place in a stretch of water’.","Americanized form of French   Chalut  ."]},{"name":"Shelly","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Shelley  ."]},{"name":"Shealy","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Shelley  ."]},{"name":"Sheeley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Shelley  ."]},{"name":"Sheely","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Shelley  ."]},{"name":"Sheley","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Shelley  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":57,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Shelley was born about 1398, in Rye, Sussex, England as the son of William Shelley. He married Elizabeth Petit in 1427, in Rye, Sussex, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 31 August 1472, in Saint Dunstan and All Saints Church, Stepney, Middlesex, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"about 1398–31 August 1472":"umbes 1398–31. august 1472","1394–1430":"1394–1430","1398–1472":"1398–1472","–Male":"Surnud","1413–1517":"1413–1517","1428–1486":"1428–1486","1430–1517":"1430–1517","–Female":"Surnud","1376–1399":"1376–1399","1472":"1472","1394":"1394","about 1428":"umbes 1428","1413":"1413","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1486":"1486","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","about 1398":"umbes 1398","31 August 1472":"31. august 1472","1517":"1517","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Hunsdon, Hertfordshire, England":"Hunsdon, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saint Dunstan and All Saints Church, Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Saint Dunstan and All Saints Church, Stepney, Middlesex, England","Rye, Sussex, , England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England"},"fi":{"about 1398–31 August 1472":"noin 1398–31. elokuuta 1472","1394–1430":"1394–1430","1398–1472":"1398–1472","–Male":"Kuollut","1413–1517":"1413–1517","1428–1486":"1428–1486","1430–1517":"1430–1517","–Female":"Kuollut","1376–1399":"1376–1399","1472":"1472","1394":"1394","about 1428":"noin 1428","1413":"1413","1455":"1455","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1486":"1486","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","about 1398":"noin 1398","31 August 1472":"31. elokuuta 1472","1517":"1517","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Hunsdon, Hertfordshire, England":"Hunsdon, Hertfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Saint Dunstan and All Saints Church, Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Saint Dunstan and All Saints Church, Stepney, Middlesex, England","Rye, Sussex, , England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England"},"fr":{"about 1398–31 August 1472":"environ 1398–31 août 1472","1394–1430":"1394–1430","1398